<section xml:id="sec-poly-zeros" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Real Zeros and Multiplicity</title>

  <p>
    If <m>(x-r)^{m}</m> is a factor of a polynomial function <m>f</m> (where <m>m</m> is the <em>highest exponent</em> possible), then <m>r</m> is called a <em>real zero of multiplicity <m>m</m> of <m>f</m> </em>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        If <m>r</m> has <em>odd</em> multiplicity, the graph will <em>cross</em> the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x=r</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            The sign of <m>f(x)</m> <em>changes</em> from one side to the other.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>
        If <m>r</m> has <em>even</em> multiplicity, the graph will <em>bounce</em> the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x=r</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            The sign of <m>f(x)</m> <em>does not change</em> from one side to the other.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>NOTE: Vocabulary</alert>  The following statements are equivalent for polynomial functions:
  </p>

  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <m>r</m> is a real number for which <em> <m>f(r)=0</m> </em>
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>r</m> is a <em>real zero</em> of the polynomial function <m>f</m>
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>r</m> is a <em>root</em> of the polynomial function <m>f</m>
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>r</m> is an <em> <m>x</m>-intercept</em> of the graph of <m>f</m>
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>(x-r)</m> is a <em>factor</em> of the graph of <m>f</m>
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>r</m> is a <em>real solution</em> of the equation <m>f(x)=0</m>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</section>